Working Output

The reconciliation system generates synthetic transaction data and bank settlement data with realistic settlement delays. It then introduces controlled anomalies to simulate real-world reconciliation challenges.

The system performs reconciliation between both datasets and produces:

Detected reconciliation issues
Duplicate settlement entries
Summary statistics
Issue breakdown by category

This enables quick identification of discrepancies between platform transactions and bank settlements.

Production Limitations

While the system demonstrates core reconciliation logic, the following limitations exist in a production environment:

1. Transaction ID Assumptions

The system assumes that transaction IDs are unique and reliable.
In real-world systems:

IDs may be reused
IDs may differ between systems
Mapping tables may be required
2. Timezone & Banking Holiday Handling

The current implementation does not account for:

Timezone differences
Banking holidays
Weekend settlement delays
Cut-off times

These factors can impact settlement timing in production systems.

3. Scalability Constraints

The current implementation uses Pandas row iteration, which may not scale efficiently for:

Millions of transactions
High-frequency reconciliation
Real-time processing

Production systems should consider:

Vectorized Pandas operations
Dask / PySpark for large datasets
Database-based reconciliation
Batch processing pipelines
